P(n): 2 + 4 + ... + 2n = (n + 2)(n - 1)
n \ge 2
P(2): 2n = (n + 2)(n - 1) \implies 2(2) = (2 + 2)(2 - 1) \implies 4 = 4,
P(3): 2n = (n + 2)(n - 1) \implies 2(3) = (3 + 2)(3 - 1) \implies 6 = 10
2 + 4 + \cdots + 2n = 2(1 + 2 + \cdots + n) = 2 \cdot \left(\dfrac{n(n+1)}{2}\right) = n(n+1)
P(n)
P(n):\quad2 + 4 +\cdots + n = n(n+1)
P(2): \quad 2 + 4 = (2)(2 + 1) = 6
P(k): 2 + 4 \cdots + 2k = k(k+1)
P(k+1)
P(k+1): 2 + 4 + \cdots + 2k + 2(k+1) = (k+1)(k+2)
